Loans data: features exploration

Dzianis Sokalau

7/16/2017

Before we took a first look on the Lending club loans data. You can find information by the link bellow: https://dzianissokalau.github.io/projects/loans/1-loans-data-first-look.html

On this note I want to explore features usefull for loan evaluation.

The data is from https://www.kaggle.com/wendykan/lending-club-loan-data
Original source is Lending Club: https://www.lendingclub.com/info/download-data.action

What features we shouldn’t use for future model

The data contain a lot of features. Some of them are primary, some are the result of following calculations / evaluations. I’m not going to explore features that show loans’ evaluation since they are already the product of scorring calculated by others. Those features are “int_rate”, “grade” and “sub_grade”.

Features

From various of features in the data set I would choose those which describe numbers (income, loan amount), loans category (purpose, term), borrower profile (public records, delinquencies, accounts etc), time (when loan was issued) and location (state).

Purposes

Let’s begin from purposes.

df %>%
  group_by(purpose) %>%
  summarise(prob = mean(result), count = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(prob))
## # A tibble: 14 x 3
##               purpose      prob  count
##                 <chr>     <dbl>  <int>
##  1            wedding 0.8609272   1963
##  2                car 0.8582931   3726
##  3     major_purchase 0.8311748   6486
##  4        educational 0.8276923    325
##  5   home_improvement 0.8095664  15638
##  6        credit_card 0.8062208  52405
##  7           vacation 0.7963746   1655
##  8              house 0.7941860   1720
##  9   renewable_energy 0.7717391    276
## 10 debt_consolidation 0.7713001 156572
## 11            medical 0.7631931   2994
## 12              other 0.7592555  14937
## 13             moving 0.7529357   2129
## 14     small_business 0.6811302   4955

The most stable are wedding and car loans (more than 85% of them are good). Hovewer thay take around 2% of all loans in the sample. Debt consolidation is the most frequent purpose of debts it takes about 59% with average share of good loans 77%. Loans for small business are the worst in the sample in terms returning (only 68% of them is paid by borrowers). As we can see purpose is a good feature to use. Depands on it probability of loan to be paid vary from 68% to 86%.

It can be interesting to look on interaction between amount, purposes and loan status.

ggplot(df, aes(as.factor(purpose), loan_amnt, fill = factor(result, labels = c("not", "yes")))) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Result Depends on Amount", x = "Purpose", y = "Amount") +   
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="If paid")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45,hjust=1))

Bad loans are usualy have higher amount depends on purpose than good ones.

States

addr_state - The state provided by the borrower in the loan application.

# Let's create table with probability of loan repayment by state first
states_prob <- df %>% 
  group_by(addr_state) %>%
  summarise(prob = mean(result), count = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(prob))

# Also we need to add full state names (for map drawing)
states_prob <- merge(states_prob, states_dict, by = "addr_state", all.x = T)

# Now let's map it
ggplot(states_prob, aes(map_id = state)) + 
  geom_map(aes(fill = prob), map = fifty_states) + 
  expand_limits(x = fifty_states$long, y = fifty_states$lat) +
  coord_map() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = NULL) + 
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = NULL) +
  labs(title = "Probability of loan repayment by state (lighter - better)", x = "", y = "") +
  theme(legend.position = "None", 
        panel.background = element_blank()) + 
  fifty_states_inset_boxes()

Some states some states have higher (maximum is 100%) probability of loan repayment and some lower (minimum is 69%). A good idea is generalizing States in the groups (for future modelling).

df <- merge(df, 
            data.frame(addr_state = states_prob[,1], state_group = states_prob[,2]), 
            by = "addr_state", all.x = T)

# spliting by 3 groups
df$state_group <- factor(cut2(unlist(df$state_group), g=3), 
                         labels = c("low", "medium", "high")) 

# checking
df %>% 
  group_by(state_group) %>% 
  summarise(prob = mean(result), count = n())
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   state_group      prob  count
##        <fctr>     <dbl>  <int>
## 1         low 0.7580926  90824
## 2      medium 0.7860953 106094
## 3        high 0.8055124  68863

Not bad split I guess.

Term

term - the number of payments on the loan. Values are in months and can be either 36 or 60.

df %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  summarise(prob = mean(result), count = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(prob))
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##        term      prob  count
##       <chr>     <dbl>  <int>
## 1 36 months 0.8198426 204399
## 2 60 months 0.6540680  61382

The shorter term is the more likely loan to be paid.

## 11    9 years 0.7735081 10071
## 12        n/a 0.6898100 10687

“n/a” (probably means person is unemployed) in emp_length reduces chances for loan repayment significantly. Let’s create an additional variable “emp_na” (1 if emp_length == “n/a”, and 0 if emp_length != “n/a”).

df$emp_na <- 0
df[df$emp_length == "n/a", "emp_na"] <- 1

It probably makes sence to convert emp_length to integer.

df[df$emp_length == "n/a", "emp_length"] <- "0"
regexp <- "[[:digit:]]+"
df$emp_length <- as.integer(str_extract(df$emp_length, regexp))

df %>%
  group_by(emp_length) %>%
  summarise(prob = mean(result), count = n()) %>%
  arrange(emp_length)

dti

dti is a ratio calculated using the borrower’s total monthly debt payments on the total debt obligations, excluding mortgage and the requested LC loan, divided by the borrower’s self-reported. monthly income. dti combines information considered above (loan’s amount, borrower’s income and term) but in the same time it is a very good indicator of borrower’s financial health. The hypothesis is the higher dti is the lower probability successful loan repayment. Let’s check it.

ggplot(df, aes(as.factor(purpose), dti, fill = factor(result, labels = c("not", "yes")))) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Result Depends on Income", x = "", y = "dti") +   
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="If paid")) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = quantile(df$dti, c(0.1, 0.9))) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=45,hjust=1))

emp_title

emp_title - the job title supplied by the Borrower when applying for the loan. This time I’m not going to explore job titles since there are too many variants. It could be a topic for an additional research. But I noticed that empty job title can reduce chanses of successful loan repayment, so let’s explore this feature.

df$jobtitle_empty <- 0
df[is.na(df$emp_title) == T, "jobtitle_empty"] <- 1

open_acc and total_acc

open_acc - the number of open credit lines in the borrower’s credit file. total_acc - the total number of credit lines currently in the borrower’s credit file. Obviously number of accounts in borrower’s file will hardly give us good probability split. But if we will calculate share of active accounts in total accaunts it will give us new good feature.

df$act_tot_acc <- df$open_acc / df$total_acc

p1 <- ggplot(df, aes(factor(result, labels = c("not", "yes")), open_acc)) +
        geom_boxplot() +
        labs(title = "", x = "Result", y = "Open accounts") +
        scale_y_continuous(limits = quantile(df$open_acc, c(0.1, 0.9))) +   
        theme_minimal()

p2 <- ggplot(df, aes(factor(result, labels = c("not", "yes")), total_acc)) +
        geom_boxplot() +
        labs(title = "", x = "Result", y = "Total accounts") +
        scale_y_continuous(limits = quantile(df$total_acc, c(0.1, 0.9))) +   
        theme_minimal()
      
p3 <- ggplot(df, aes(factor(result, labels = c("not", "yes")), act_tot_acc)) +
        geom_boxplot() +
        labs(title = "", x = "Result", y = "Ratio") +
        scale_y_continuous(limits = quantile(df$act_tot_acc, c(0.1, 0.9))) +   
        theme_minimal()

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, ncol = 3, nrow = 1)

It isn’t super high improvement but median of ratio is a little bit different between paid and not paid loans.

tot_cur_bal

tot_cur_bal - total current balance of all accounts

# let's convert n/a to 0 first and convert variable to numeric
df[is.na(df$tot_cur_bal) == T, "tot_cur_bal"] <- 0
df$tot_cur_bal <- as.numeric(df$tot_cur_bal)

# now the data is ready to be vizualized
ggplot(df, aes(tot_cur_bal, fill = factor(result, labels = c("not", "yes")))) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.4) +
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="If paid")) +
  xlim(0,100000) +
  labs(title = "", x = "Balance", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

n/a (or 0) in tot_cur_bal increasing chances of successful loan repayment. Let’s create an additional variable to split zero and nonzero values.

df$zero_bal <- 0
df[df$tot_cur_bal == 0, 'zero_bal'] <- 1

# and we've got following
df %>%
  group_by(zero_bal) %>%
  summarise(prob = mean(result), count = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(prob))

open_il_6m, open_il_12m and open_il_24m

open_il_6m - number of currently active installment trades. open_il_12m - number of installment accounts opened in past 12 months. open_il_24m - number of installment accounts opened in past 24 months.

There are small group of borrowers with currently active or opened installment accounts in past 24 months.

nrow(df[is.na(df$open_il_6m) == F | is.na(df$open_il_12m) == F | is.na(df$open_il_24m) == F, ])
## [1] 144

let’s create new variable shows if there were any installment accounts oppened in past.

df$open_il <- 0
df[is.na(df$open_il_6m) == F | is.na(df$open_il_12m) == F | is.na(df$open_il_24m) == F, "open_il"] <- 1
